items.title: Hanson's tweet 'unfit for afternoon tea but not racist', lawyer argues
items.standfirst: H anson is appealing a decision that found a 2022 tweet against a Greens senator was "seriously offensive" and intimidating.
items.content: Pauline Hanson was not driven by racism but rather a need to expose hypocrisy when she told a Greens senator to pack her bags and return to Pakistan.That is the One Nation leader's argument as she challenges court findings she engaged in "seriously offensive" and intimidating behaviour toward Greens deputy leader Mehreen Faruqi.Hanson's remarks in September 2022 - while not fit for an afternoon tea or the courtroom - were expected by Australian Twitter users accustomed to the argy-bargy of politicians, barrister Sue Chrysanthou SC argued during a Federal Court appeal hearing today.READ MORE: Trump's stunning Epstein files U-turnThe court could not sit in an ivory tower without grappling with how Twitter users conducted themselves in 2022, often writing things they would not say in person, the barrister said.Hanson's post was an attack on Faruqi's personal views on the death of Queen Elizabeth II and was not driven by her race, colour, national or ethnic origin, the barrister said.The day of the Queen's death, Faruqi took to Twitter, now known as X, to offer condolences to those who knew the monarch.But she added she could not mourn the passing of the leader of a "racist empire built on stolen lives, land and wealth of colonised peoples".In a response, Hanson said she was appalled and disgusted by the comments.READ MORE: Trump's bitter attack after being called 'most unpopular president of all time'"When you immigrated to Australia you took every advantage of this country," she wrote."It's clear you're not happy, so pack your bags and piss off back to Pakistan."The court's finding these remarks actually intimidated Australian migrants of colour was extreme, Chrysanthou told the court.Hanson's tweet was made following hours of posts by others making similar accusations against the Greens deputy leader, she said.She pointed out Faruqi's alleged hypocrisy by criticising the country while deciding to immigrate here, buying property and living off taxpayer-funded income as a senator, the barrister said.READ MORE: Huge threat prompting multiple countries to bring back military draftIn finding the One Nation leader had engaged in racism, Justice Angus Stewart failed to take this context into account, the court was told.The Greens' then-leader Adam Bandt had also been told to get out of Australia after he called for a republic on the day the Queen died, Chrysanthou pointed out.Hanson's post also did not refer to any ethnic group, for instance saying, "Piss off back to Pakistan and so should everyone else from Pakistan.""It's not necessarily a racially motivated reason to say to that person, 'Why don't you just leave? If you don't like it here, leave'," Chrysanthou said.READ MORE: NSW Nationals leader shocks fellow MPs with surprise resignationHanson's tweet was found to have breached 18C of the Racial Discrimination Act - a clause that has survived repeated efforts by conservative politicians to strike it out.In his November 2024 findings, Justice Stewart found that migrants of colour, Australians who had recently immigrated, or Muslims who were people of colour in Australia would be insulted, offended, humiliated and intimidated by the tweet."It is a message that Senator Faruqi is, as an immigrant, a second-class citizen, and that she should be grateful for what she has and keep quiet," he said in his Federal Court ruling.The phrase "go back to where you came from" was a racist, anti-immigrant and nativist trope traceable to the White Australia Policy, the judge declared.The appeal hearing continues.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. Available on the Apple App Store and Google Play.

items.title: Violent youth offenders flown to the Gold Coast on taxpayer-funded trip
items.standfirst: The NDIS-funded interstate trip took place in a bid to "break the cycle of re-offending".
items.content: T wo violent youth offenders from Melbourne were flown to Queensland on a holiday funded by the National Disability Insurance Scheme (NDIS), it has been revealed.The Victorian teenagers had their Community Corrections Orders (CCO) amended by the state's Department of Justice and Community Safety to be allowed on a taxpayer-funded interstate trip to visit theme parks on the Gold Coast.It is understood the teens had been convicted of violent home invasions and carjackings but were not jailed.READ MORE: Huge threat prompting multiple countries to bring back military draftREAD MORE: Trump's bitter attack after being called 'most unpopular president of all time'9News understands it took place within the past few months and involved sightseeing and a visit to the popular theme parks.Victorian Premier Jacinta Allan said "no youth justice officials were involved in accompanying these young people".Allan also confirmed the state's youth justice system did not fund the trip. "What we are making it very clear in Victoria is that there are consequences for offending," Allan said.Victoria's opposition leader Brad Battin said convicted youth offenders should not be "going off on holidays"."At the moment, we're seeing kids go to Europe and possibly up to the Gold Coast," Battin said."Where is the message to kids to say that crime doesn't pay here in Victoria?" In a statement, a spokesperson for the NDIS said it was investigating the claims."The NDIS provides disability-related supports to all eligible Australians," the spokesperson told 9News. "The NDIS is not responsible for the rehabilitation of youth offenders."DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. items.content: Police search two homes linked to a suspect in the investigation into the murder of Adelaide woman Rosemary Brown and the disappearance of her 15-year-old daughter, Melissa Trussell.

items.title: Police say people are hiding information about horror cold case after latest search
items.standfirst: Rosemary Brown, 33, and Melissa Trussell, 15, were last seen in Blair Athol in Adelaide's north at about 2.30am on Saturday 13 May 2000.
items.content: SA Police have insisted members of the public are hiding information about the cold case murders of a mum and daughter after officers finished their latest search linked to the alleged killings. Rosemary Brown, 33, and Melissa Trussell, 15, were last seen in Blair Athol in Adelaide's north at about 2.30am on Saturday, May 13, 2000.Police say Brown was murdered and it's likely Trussell was too, but her body has never been found. READ MORE: Trump hints at decision on Venezuela - is the US about to go to war?The mother's body was discovered in mangroves at Garden Island in the city on Sunday, July 2, 2000.Detective Superintendent Darren Fielke said this afternoon that detectives they know people are hiding something."Police are aware of members of the public who have information who have not come forward or have not assisted police,'' he said."This is the murder of a mother and her 15-year-old daughter. The remains of Melissa have not been found.READ MORE: Giant US warship arrives in Caribbean as part of Trump military build-up"Put yourselves in the shoes of the family of Rosemary and Melissa – they want answers about what happened to their loved ones and to recover Melissa's remains."Your information may be the missing piece of the puzzle that leads to the family getting the answers they deserve.''Detective Superintendent Fielke said detectives have identified "several suspects" and have searched two homes connected with one.READ MORE: Boy, 14, on bail allegedly stabs 19-year-old on quiet Melbourne streetBut they believe more than one person was involved in the murders and disposal of the bodies. "To those who played a minor role, or who may have found themselves in a situation they couldn't remove themselves from – now is the time to come forward and tell your story," he said.A knife has also been found, with DNA testing being done.Two cars of interest have been identified.However, a submerged vehicle found at Garden Island and bones found at Osborne are not unrelated, police say.Police revisited the case in August.A former police diver exclusively told 9News of his role in the investigation, while supporting the fresh search for answers.A million dollar reward is on offer leading to a conviction over the suspected murder of Melissa Trussell and $20,000 over that of Rosemary Brown.

Police searched two homes linked to a suspect in the cold case.
Rosemary Brown and Melissa Trussell were last seen in 2000.
Police say people are hiding information about the case.
The case involves a murdered mother and missing daughter.

clusters.neutral_headline: NSW Nationals Leader Resigns, Shocking Fellow MPs

items.title: NSW Nationals leader shocks fellow MPs with surprise resignation
items.standfirst: A fter ousting his predecessor in a 2023 leadership spill.
items.content: N SW Nationals leader Dugald Saunders has quit after a two-and-a-half-year tenure in a move that has "surprised" some party colleagues.Dubbo MP Saunders confirmed his immediate resignation in a statement to the media, describing his decision to step down as a "difficult" one."It's been an honour to lead the parliamentary team during a challenging time in opposition and I've always done my best to represent regional NSW," Saunders said.READ MORE: Huge threat prompting multiple countries to bring back the military draft "It's a difficult decision but it is the right time for me to take a step back and focus more on my family and myself."It's also the right time to allow a new leader to take up the fight ahead of the next election."Saunders said he would continue to serve in his role as Dubbo's local member, a position he has retained since 2019.He took on the job of NSW Nationals Leader in 2023 after Paul Toole was ousted in a leadership spill.Saunders was also appointed shadow minister for agriculture, trade and natural resources in 2024 and shadow minister for regional NSW in 2023. Federal Nationals MP Michael McCormack told media he was "surprised" by the news."He has always stood up for regional people's interests and I wish him all the very best for the future," McCormack said.READ MORE: Boy, 14, on bail allegedly stabs 19-year-old on quiet Melbourne streetNationals MPs are scheduled to meet in Sydney tomorrow, however it remains unknown if Saunders' replacement will be decided then. Cootamundra MP Steph Cooke has been named as a potential contender to fill his seat."If she wants to put a hand up, I'd certainly support that," McCormack said of Cooke.Saunders leaves the job in a tumultuous time for the Nationals, after the Liberal Party last week confirmed it would abandon its net zero 2050 target following bitter division among Coalition ranks. He had a career in broadcasting at the ABC before entering politics.The NSW MP notably worked for the national broadcaster during the 2000 Sydney Olympics.
